Shuttle-C does well enough for seed factories and to get/hold attention to get a few more launches out there, to plant a seed factory which is the initial processing facility and builds the mass-driver engine to bring it back. Soyuz works well enough for crewed access, until we get the OSP.<br>
 We don't need CNTs or beanstalks to make things happen. We just need to use what we've got in intelligent ways.<br>
<br>
The reason to go to an NEA is <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://neofuel.com">fuel</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
Unless we jump right into using weapons-grade fissionables for in-space propulsion right away (I'm all for it, but...), we need H2O, CH4, CO2, etc.<br>
If you've got water, you can do anything. Without a ready source, you're starved and dependant on the Earthworm's politicians for funding. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Administrator</span><br>  Posts: 981<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/23/03 1:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=773.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Our next step in space?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Going right to Mars, as Mars Direct does, is good because it's a simple sound bite for the short-attention-span media, politicians or the public. &quot;What's a station for?&quot; or &quot;Why go to an NEA&quot;? they ask, and by the time you start explaining, they've fallen asleep again...<br>
